															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-gears" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(172464); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=172464&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226081" alt="Dr Gears" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=172464)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-gears" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(172464); return false;" >Dr Gears</a></span> <span class="odate time_1250608206 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">18 Aug 2009 15:10</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-563877">
									

<p>This is great! It feels like old school, golden age Sci-Fi at it's best. You get the occasional hints ("Upper eye…wtf?"), but the big bang is held off perfectly. I can see how this would be uplifting, in a way…but i find it chilling. These beings have ashed out their own world, and are dieing. A drowning man will often drown or seriously injure their rescuer in their mad flailing to get up and away from the water, and in to the air, often drowning them both. What will happen when a whole planet of drowning beings suddenly realizes that there is another place, one of safety and plenty…</p>
<p>Gave me a good shiver, excellent work!!</p>

							</div>

								
